    "answer_en": "We prioritize rigorous quality control at every stage – from planting to harvesting.  We conduct regular checks on the maize for disease, pest, and nutrient deficiencies.  We also work closely with the National Genebank to ensure compliance with export standards.  Proper drying and storage are also vital."
  },
  {
    "question_en": "Can you explain the importance of the National Genebank in Malawi’s agricultural sector?",
    "answer_en": "The National Genebank is absolutely critical! It’s a repository of genetic resources – seeds, plants, and genetic information – that are vital for maintaining Malawi’s agricultural diversity and resilience.  It’s a cornerstone of our efforts to improve crop yields and adapt to climate change."
  },
  {
    "question_en": "What are some of the most common pests affecting maize crops in Malawi, and how can farmers protect their crops?",
    "answer_en": "Several pests are a concern – maize borers, aphids, and fall armyworms.  We emphasize integrated pest management (IPM) – using a combination of methods – including crop rotation, biological control, and targeted pesticide applications only when necessary.  Regular scouting is key to early detection."
  },
  {
    "question_en": "What are the benefits of using locally adapted maize varieties?",
    "answer_en": "Locally adapted maize varieties are crucial because they are better suited to the local climate, soil conditions, and pest pressures.  They often have higher yields and are more resistant to diseases, reducing the need for expensive inputs."
  },
  {
    "question_en": "How can farmers access information and training on best practices for maize production?",
    "answer_en": "We provide farmers with extension services, workshops, and field demonstrations.  We also have a network of agricultural extension officers who are available to provide personalized advice and support.  We also utilize mobile technology to disseminate information."
  }
