    "answer_en": "The most important thing is to actively manage insect populations.  Regularly inspect your plants for aphids and beetles, and take steps to control them.  This includes using appropriate netting, sticky traps, and potentially introducing beneficial insects like ladybugs.  Also, ensuring good sanitation – removing crop debris – can help reduce the availability of host plants for insects."
  },
  {
    "question_en": "I’m having trouble with soybean diseases like brown spot and bactery blight. What are some effective control methods I can use?",
    "answer_en": "Those diseases are challenging, but we have several options.  Rotting of symptomatic plants is a common way to reduce the spread of these diseases.  We also use preventative measures like using resistant varieties and rotating crops with non-host plants like maize or sorghum.  For brown spot, we can apply fungicides, and for bactery blight, we focus on good sanitation and ensuring proper drainage to prevent root rot.  Remember, early detection is key!"
